#circuitbreakersg day 31 
Had homemade ban mian 板面 🍜 for dinner because noodle-making is so fun and I wanted to try making a different type of noodles apart from pasta. 😃
.
.
.
Soup stock was made using pork bones, chicken bones, soya beans and ikan bilis, which were simmering in the slow cooker since last night. .
.
.
Given the amount of preparation that went behind making what looks like a simple dish, it may seem to make more sense simply buying this from the coffee shop. However, the satisfaction that I got from making this dish (and many other dishes) from scratch, is immense. ☺️
.
.
.
Which is why, I will continue to cook, whenever I can. 🙂 And I’m grateful that I am able to. #gratitudediary
.
.
.
.

@healing.with.sam I saw! What a coincidence and your looks really delicious!! 🤤😋
@28nankinstreet thank you!! I love yours too😊😍
Oooo lovely! I also did ban mian today too! But a dry version :))))
Your balls of noodles look so cute!
@_pineconesnbasil thanks! I’m sure your mee hoon kueh was good! 😊
Ooh looks good 😍😋 I tried making mee hoon kueh once... 😜
@ainz_gourmet I added soy beans coz that is one of the ingredients which usually helps to make the soup stock more flavourful but it’s not a must-have. ☺️
@28nankinstreet 👍🏼 soy bean milk or the bean itself?

I love pan mee (Cantonese)! Will need to include this in my to cook list ☺️ Didn’t know the stock includes soy. And your noodle looks good too. 
Can’t agree more with you on the satisfaction from own cooking. I like how I can control what I like/don’t like, have lots of veges/meat etc.
@kaitsdish thanks! ☺️ It’s my new found ‘hobby’ so I think there will be more noodle-making in the near future! 😂
@28nankinstreet it's very therapeutic, in my opinion. Go for it! 😍
I love making noodles at home as well! Noodles look delicious with the fish toppings! 😍👍
Oh my goodness yummy. One of my favs. Yes, sometimes the simplest things can be the most complicated
